    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kinda yellow and pale compared to the top ones. what's probably going on with them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves, especially on the lower parts of the plant, can be a common issue. It's likely due to a lack of light, as the lower leaves are farther away from the sun's rays. You might want to consider pruning the plant to encourage new growth and prevent the lower leaves from becoming too leggy. This is a common problem for tomato plants, especially when they're not getting enough direct sunlight. \n\nIt's also possible that the soil is too wet, which can cause root rot and lead to yellowing leaves. Make sure the soil drains well and isn't waterlogged. A bit of research on the specific needs of your tomato plant variety can also help. \n\nYou know, I've heard that some gardeners use a technique called \"top-dressing\" to address this issue. It involves sprinkling a thin layer of compost or fertilizer on top of the soil to provide nutrients to the lower leaves. It's a bit like a gentle \"giving a boost\" to the plant's growth, rather like a friendly little imp giving a helping hand to a struggling garden gnome.",
