    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, garden gnomes? I meant the leaves are turning yellow/pale, not that the plant is dying. Is it a nutrient thing? Like, how do I check if they need nitrogen or something? I want to make sure the soil is actually okay.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Garden gnomes, yes, well, they're quite fond of a good fertilizer, aren't they? Anyway, back to your tomato plants. The yellowing leaves could be a sign of nutrient deficiencies, but it's not always a straightforward issue. \n\nNitrogen, in particular, is a common culprit when it comes to yellowing leaves. If the leaves are turning pale, it might be a sign that the plant is getting too much nitrogen. On the other hand, if the leaves are turning yellow, it could indicate a lack of nitrogen. But it's not just about nitrogen – other nutrients like iron, magnesium, and potassium can also play a role.\n\nTo check the soil, you can perform a simple test. Dig up a small sample of soil and mix it with water to create a solution. Then, add a few drops of food coloring to the solution. If the color doesn't stay in the soil for more than a few minutes, it might indicate nutrient deficiencies. \n\nIt's also worth considering the pH level of your soil. Tomato plants prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil pH, between 6.0 and 7.0. If your soil is too alkaline or too acidic, it can affect nutrient availability",
      "source": "target",
